The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, December 31, 2003  The City Diary
																																																																																		A garment and gift shop on CIT Road, opposite ESI Hospital, in the Maniktala police station area, was burgled early on Tuesday. Police said the miscreants broke into the shop through the vent of an air-conditioning machine that had been sealed with a plywood board. They took away Rs 90,000 in cash. Soumen Mitra, deputy commissioner of police (detective department), said he suspected that the gang sent in a child through the vent, approximately seven feet above road level. No arrests have been made yet.																																																		An assessment officer in the Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC) faces dismissal after 17 years of service as the Scheduled Caste certificate submitted by him has been found to be fake during verification. According to mayor Subrata Mukherjee, the officer joined the civic body in 1986. Following a complaint against him, the CMC wrote to the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes authority to ascertain the authenticity of his certificate.																																																		Four persons were arrested and goods worth Rs 6 lakh recovered on Monday night from Ghutiarisharif, in South 24-Parganas, by the detective department. 																																																								ccording to Soumen Mitra, deputy commissioner (detective department), Ehsan Sheikh and Abdul Kasim were rounded up for stealing ball bearings worth Rs 9 lakh on November 27 from a warehouse on Taratala Road. 																																																								wo others, who acted as agents to sell the stolen goods, were picked up from their respective homes. The duo was identified as Ram Lakhan Gupta, of Jorasanko, and Lal Chand Shaw, of Ganesh Chandra Avenue, in central Calcutta. Sleuths said more arrests were in the offing.																																																		Twin fires broke out on Tuesday. In the first incident, the ground-floor storeroom of the Survey of India building, on Wood Street, in the Shakespeare Sarani police station area, was gutted. It took two fire tenders about an hour to douse the flames. Fire engulfed a bar on AJC Bose Road in the second incident. Three fire tenders doused the flames. No casualty was reported in either incident.																																																		A 35-year-old man, Narayan Pasi, was run over on Tuesday afternoon on Taratala Road by a speeding luxury bus. According to police, local residents put up a 10-minute roadblock to protest the death. The driver was arrested and the bus impounded.																																																		A bus overturned on the Matapara-Howrah route at about 9.30 am on Tuesday, but none of the passengers received any injuries. There were about 60 people on board when the driver lost control over his vehicle while trying to overtake a lorry at high speed. The bus crashed into a paddy field.							TO LIONS CLUB OF CALCUTTA SANJEEVANI for organising a free eye operation camp, in collaboration with Sradha Eyecare, for 80 poor patients
